-- ── Compare JSON ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Compare JSON refers to the category of free, browser-based utilities used to diff two JSON documents and highlight added, removed, or changed keys and values. These tools (such as jsondiff.com, jsoncompare.org, and json-diff.com) typically run entirely in the browser, require no signup, and are aimed at developers who need a quick way to spot differences between JSON payloads, config files, or API responses.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(NULL, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$Not publicly disclosed$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Not publicly disclosed$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Compare JSON: Free Online JSON Diff and Comparison Tool$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Compare two JSON documents online for free. Spot added, removed, and changed keys instantly with a browser-based JSON diff and comparison utility.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Compare JSON describes a widely used category of free, web-based utilities that let developers paste, upload, or link two JSON documents and instantly see the differences between them. Rather than being a single branded company with a public corporate history, tools in this category (examples include jsondiff.com, jsoncompare.org, jsoncompare.io, json-diff.com, and jsondiffs.com) are typically small, independently operated developer utilities, several of which are open source, that share a common purpose and feature set. The core function is a semantic JSON diff: instead of a plain text line-by-line comparison, these tools parse both JSON documents into their underlying key-value structure and identify which keys were added, which were removed, and which values changed, even if the raw formatting, whitespace, or key ordering differs between the two documents. This semantic approach matters because two JSON files that are functionally identical can still look completely different as plain text if keys are reordered or whitespace differs, so a naive text diff would produce a lot of false positives. Most Compare JSON style tools also bundle adjacent utilities: JSON validation to check that a document is syntactically correct, JSON formatting and pretty-printing to make minified or compact JSON readable, and options to ignore key order or whitespace when performing the comparison. Common presentation modes include a side-by-side split view, a unified tree view that lets users expand and collapse nested objects and arrays, and color-coded highlighting (commonly green for additions, red for deletions, and yellow or orange for modified values). Input methods typically include pasting raw JSON text directly, uploading two separate JSON files for comparison, or in some tools fetching JSON directly from two URLs, which is useful for comparing API responses across environments such as staging versus production. Nearly all tools in this category are free to use with no account or signup required, and many explicitly advertise that JSON data is processed client-side in the browser rather than being uploaded to a server, which matters for developers comparing sensitive configuration or payload data. Typical use cases include comparing API response payloads before and after a backend change, diffing configuration files across environments, checking internationalization or localization files for missing translation keys, validating that a data migration preserved the correct structure, and reviewing changes to structured data during code review. Because this is a category of similar independent tools rather than a single vendor, specific company details such as founding year, headquarters, team size, and formal pricing tiers are not publicly disclosed in the way they would be for a venture-backed software company; the tools instead function as free public utilities maintained by individual developers or small teams. When evaluating a Compare JSON tool, developers typically look for whether it processes data locally in the browser (for privacy with sensitive payloads), whether it supports large JSON files without freezing, whether it has a semantic diff mode versus a plain text mode, and whether it supports both file upload and direct paste input.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '828ccb91-4556-45c0-86bd-d17dd4c415b4';

